Adebola Williams
writes on
Monday, April 12
Adebola Williams is an entrepreneur, journalist, political activist and motivational speaker. He is the Group CEO of Red; co-founded and runs Red Africa, Africa’s largest portfolio of youth media brands which include Red Media Africa, Statecraft Inc, The Future Awards Africa and YNaija.  <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-284639" src="https://i1.wp.com/leadership.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/p1.png?resize=414%2C528&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="414" height="528" data-recalc-dims="1" /> Ayisha Osori
writes on
Wednesday, April 14
Ayisha Osori, is a lawyer, consultant and communication strategist in the public and private sectors. She has consulted for the World Bank, United Nations Development Fund, United Nations Children’s Fund, the Department for International Development, the Royal Institute of International Affairs and the National Centre for Women’s Development on women’s empowerment and gender mainstreaming of development.  <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-284640" src="https://i2.wp.com/leadership.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/p2.png?resize=362%2C530&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="362" height="530" data-recalc-dims="1" /> Eedris Abdulkareem
writes on FRIday, April 16
Eedris Abdulkareem is a-talented artiste, singer, songwriter, less known for his sporting prowess than for music. Born in Kano, his parents hail from south western Nigeria.
He represented Nigeria in the cadet division of table tennis at the All Africa Games in Nairobi in 1989 and won a bronze medal. He later won trophies in the 1991 Coca-Cola Open in Lagos, 1992 Pepsi Open in Kano and the 1994 Elephant Cement Open in Abeokuta.
But he succumbed to his old passion, music, in 1997 when he formed the “The Remedies” band.  <img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-284641" src="https://i2.wp.com/leadership.ng/wp-content/uploads/2021/04/p3.png?resize=431%2C514&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="431" height="514" data-recalc-dims="1" />  Monday, April 12, LEADERSHIP continues its series of conversations to highlight alternative voices in Nigeria’s search for a pathway. Don’t miss it!